{"award_age":46.0,"bio_image":"full\/380cbeb670affa8a9598a00659d34ffeac28f8cf.jpg","category":"Literature","country":"Norway","date_of_birth":"1882-05-20T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1949-06-10T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"female","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/1\/14\/Sigrid_Undset_1928.jpg\/220px-Sigrid_Undset_1928.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sigrid_Undset","mini_bio":"<p><b>Sigrid Undset<\/b> (20 May 1882 \u2013 10 June 1949) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norwegian_language\" title=\"Norwegian language\">Norwegian<\/a> novelist who was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Literature\">Nobel Prize for Literature<\/a> in 1928.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sigrid_Undset#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Undset was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kalundborg\" title=\"Kalundborg\">Kalundborg<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denmark\" title=\"Denmark\">Denmark<\/a>, but her family moved to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norway\" title=\"Norway\">Norway<\/a> when she was two years old. In 1924, she converted to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Roman_Catholic_Church\" title=\"Roman Catholic Church\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Roman Catholicism<\/a>. She fled Norway for the United States in 1940 because of her opposition to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nazi_Germany\" title=\"Nazi Germany\">Nazi Germany<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Operation_Weser%C3%BCbung\" title=\"Operation Weser\u00fcbung\">German occupation<\/a>, but returned after <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II<\/a> ended in 1945.<\/p><p>Her best-known work is <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kristin_Lavransdatter\" title=\"Kristin Lavransdatter\">Kristin Lavransdatter<\/a><\/i>, a trilogy about life in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Scandinavia\" title=\"Scandinavia\">Scandinavia<\/a> in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Middle_Ages\" title=\"Middle Ages\">Middle Ages<\/a>, portrayed through the experiences of a woman from birth until death. Its three volumes were published between 1920 and 1922. Undset's Nobel Prize was awarded partly for this work, and partly for her four-volume work <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Master_of_Hestviken\" title=\"The Master of Hestviken\">The Master of Hestviken<\/a><\/i>, published between 1925 and 1927 and dealing with similar themes.<\/p>","name":"Sigrid Undset","place_of_birth":"Kalundborg , Denmark","place_of_death":"Lillehammer , Norway","text":"Sigrid Undset , Literature, 1928","year":1928.0}